10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Thursday.</em></p><table class=3D"header=
" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Oh Wells Fargo</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/36237924.195389/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTkvaXMtdGhlLXNlYy11bmNvbnN0aXR1dGlvbmFsP2Nt=
cGlkPUJCRDA3MzAyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXd=
zbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDczMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB0259e21e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">talked in 2022</a> about reports that Wells=
 Fargo &amp; Co. did fake job interviews for fake diversity purposes. Wells=
 Fargo had rules saying that =E2=80=9Cdiverse candidates=E2=80=9D had to be=
 interviewed as part of the hiring process for certain jobs. Sometimes a jo=
b would open up, and a manager would offer it to a White man, but in order =
to comply with the rule, he would need to interview a woman or person of co=
lor before filling the job. So he=E2=80=99d call in a Black woman, intervie=
w her, and then immediately toss her resume in the garbage and give the job=
 to the White man anyway.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say=
 this is true: Let=E2=80=99s assume that Wells Fargo regularly did fake int=
erviews. Some questions:</p><ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-lef=
t: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Who was hurt=
 by it?</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">What can they do about it?=
</li></ul><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It feels like the first question sho=
uld be pretty easy to answer. Obviously the people who were called in for f=
ake interviews were hurt: Their time was wasted and they got their hopes up=
 for nothing. Also there is something good about workplace diversity, and s=
o if Wells Fargo was making fake gestures at diversity rather than actually=
 trying to hire diverse candidates, its employees and customers were harmed=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what can they do about it? It is hard=
 for an employee or a customer to sue for damages,=C2=A0saying =E2=80=9Cif =
you had done a better job of interviewing diverse candidates, I would have =
had a more pleasant experience at Wells Fargo=E2=80=9D:=C2=A0The causal cha=
in is too long and uncertain, the damages too abstract.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">The people who were fake-interviewed have a more obvious compl=
aint: They wasted an hour on the interview, maybe a few more on preparation=
. Still, the damages for =E2=80=9Cyou wasted three hours of my time=E2=80=
=9D are not that big, and probably a lot of them can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>pro=
ve=C2=A0</em>that their interviews were fake: Maybe they were=C2=A0really=
=C2=A0interviewed and just lost out to a better candidate. Of course if you=
 reviewed Wells Fargo=E2=80=99s internal emails and got testimony from ever=
yone involved, you might find some pretty clear-cut cases.=C2=A0(There=E2=
=80=99s an email from the manager to the favored candidate, the day before =
the interviews, saying =E2=80=9Cthe job is yours, just gotta do a fake inte=
rview first to check the box,=E2=80=9D etc.) But it seems impractical to su=
e: You=E2=80=99d need to get a lawyer to demand documents from Wells Fargo =
and interview witnesses and all of that, to sue for =E2=80=9Cyou wasted thr=
ee hours of my time.=E2=80=9D You could bring a class-action lawsuit on beh=
alf of=C2=A0<em>everyone=C2=A0</em>who was fake-interviewed, which would in=
crease the dollar size of the lawsuit and make it more worth a lawyer=E2=80=
=99s time, but you=E2=80=99d still have the difficult factual question of p=
roving which of them were fake-interviewed and which of them were really in=
terviewed.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh but you know the real answer =
to those questions! From the <em>first page=C2=A0</em>of Wells Fargo=E2=80=
=99s 2021 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36237924=
.195389/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzcyOTcxLzAwMDA=
wNzI5NzEyMjAwMDA5Ni93ZmMtMjAyMTEyMzEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd6b43d03=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">annual report on Form 10-K</a><a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D=
"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meeting the increasingly =
diverse needs of Wells Fargo=E2=80=99s global customer base is critical to =
our company=E2=80=99s long-term growth and success. Wells Fargo values and =
promotes diversity, equity and inclusion (DE&amp;I) in every aspect of our =
business. We are dedicated to recruitment and career development practices =
that support our employees and promote diversity in our workforce at all le=
vels of our Company, including leadership positions. We have a strong recor=
d of recruiting, promoting, and rewarding women and racially/ethnically div=
erse employees at all levels of our Company, including a commitment to incr=
ease diverse representation in leadership roles. In November 2020, a new Op=
erating Committee-level role reporting directly to our CEO was created to l=
ead DE&amp;I efforts. In this role, our Head of Diverse Segments, Represent=
ation and Inclusion is responsible for driving a Company-wide DE&amp;I stra=
tegy.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">See:=C2=A0<em>Actually=
=C2=A0</em>pursuing diversity is, in Wells Fargo=E2=80=99s own words, =E2=
=80=9Ccritical to our company=E2=80=99s long-term growth and success.=E2=80=
=9D If Wells Fargo was=C2=A0<em>pretending=C2=A0</em>to pursue diversity, t=
hen it was harming=C2=A0<em>shareholders</em>, by undermining its own long-=
term growth and success. Worse than that, though: Wells Fargo was also=C2=
=A0<em>telling=C2=A0</em>shareholders, right there in its 10-K, that it was=
 =E2=80=9Cdedicated to recruitment and career development practices that su=
pport our employees and promote diversity in our workforce,=E2=80=9D and th=
at it had =E2=80=9Ca commitment to increase diverse representation in leade=
rship roles.=E2=80=9D If that=C2=A0wasn=E2=80=99t true, then it was=C2=A0<e=
m>lying=C2=A0</em>to the shareholders. It was lying to shareholders to indu=
ce them to buy stock. It was committing securities fraud.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Wells Fargo=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/36237924.195389/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9l=
ZGdhci9kYXRhLzcyOTcxLzAwMDExOTMxMjUyMjA3NDYxMi9kMzA0MTUwZGRlZjE0YS5odG0/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB73a8f88a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">2021=C2=A0proxy statement</a> goes =
further, describing in detail =E2=80=9CHow We Seek to Improve Diverse Repre=
sentation and Inclusion within the Company.=E2=80=9D And the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36237924.195389/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
c2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzcyOTcxLzAwMDExOTMxMjUyMTA4MjkwNy9kNzE=
zMTNkZGVmMTRhLmh0bSN0b2M3MTMxM18zN2M/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc8311e3f" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">2020 proxy statement</a> laid out =E2=80=9COur Diverse Candidate Sourc=
ing and Interview Guidelines,=E2=80=9D including a requirement that, =E2=80=
=9Cfor most U.S. roles with total direct compensation greater than $100,000=
,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cat least 50% of interview candidates must be diver=
se with respect to at least one diversity dimension.=E2=80=9D Surely if tho=
se interviews were all (mostly? sometimes?) fake then that operated as a de=
ception on the shareholders? If this stuff wasn=E2=80=99t material to inves=
tors, why spend so much time describing it in investor reports?</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also: We talked about this on May 19, 2022, after a <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36237924.195389/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMi8wNS8xOS9idXNpbmVzcy93ZWxscy1mYXJnby1mYWt=
lLWludGVydmlld3MuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb187e2f5" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">New York=
 Times report</a>=C2=A0that day on the fake interviews. The Times report le=
d to questions from the Justice Department, and Wells Fargo <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36237924.195389/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMDcvd2VsbHMtZmFyZ28tcGF1c2Vz=
LWRpdmVyc2l0eS1ydWxlcy1hZnRlci1zaGFtLWludGVydmlld3MtcmVwb3J0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA=
3MzAyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJn=
V0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDczMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBc3935d55" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">=E2=80=9Cpaused=E2=80=9D its diversity hiring rules</a=
>=C2=A0on June 7. The stock closed at $42.11 on May 18, the day before the =
Times report came out, and hit $45.47 on June 7. The next day it fell, and =
by June 14 it closed at $37.43. Did the reports of fake interviews, and wor=
ries about reputational and regulatory consequences, take a couple of bucks=
 off the stock price? Sure, maybe. In June 2022, Wells Fargo had about <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36237924.195389/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvNzI5NzEvMDAwMDA3M=
jk3MTIyMDAwMTEzL3dmYy0yMDIyMDMzMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcf3037f1" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">3.8 billion shares</a> outstanding. A couple of bucks off the stock =
price is billions of dollars of harm.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Notic=
e how clean and simple this is. The shareholders can easily quantify their =
damages, or at least, they can easily=C2=A0<em>argue=C2=A0</em>for some qua=
ntity of damages. That quantity is large: If the fake interviews took $2 of=
f the stock price, then they cost shareholders $7.6 billion. So they can su=
e for $7.6 billion. The candidates who were fake-interviewed, and the emplo=
yees who faced a less diverse environment, have a tougher time quantifying =
how they were harmed; the shareholders can just point to the line on the gr=
aph that went down.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They still need to prove that Wells Fa=
rgo did (a lot of) fake interviews, but they don=E2=80=99t have to prove th=
at=C2=A0<em>any one=C2=A0</em>interview was fake.=C2=A0A candidate claiming=
 that she was fake-interviewed would have to find some evidence that,=C2=A0=
<em>in her case</em>, a manager promised the job to someone else, but a sha=
reholder doesn=E2=80=99t have to have any particular connection to any part=
icular fake interview: If Wells Fargo did 100 fake interviews, then the sha=
reholder was harmed by them, even if the shareholder never knew anything ab=
out those interviews and=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t even know Wells Fargo had =
a diversity policy</em>.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important;=
 background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Bloomberg Law=E2=80=99s <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36237924.195389/aHR0cHM6L=
y9uZXdzLmJsb29tYmVyZ2xhdy5jb20vdXMtbGF3LXdlZWsvd2VsbHMtZmFyZ28tdG8tZmFjZS1z=
ZWN1cml0aWVzLXN1aXQtb3Zlci1zaGFtLWpvYi1pbnRlcnZpZXdz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB3e8bb956" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">Isaiah Poritz reports</a>:=C2=A0</p><blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wells Fargo &amp; Co. failed to dodge a lawsuit alle=
ging the bank defrauded investors by touting a successful diversity hiring =
policy while actually conducting =E2=80=9Csham=E2=80=9D job interviews for =
minority candidates it had no intention of hiring.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Judge Trina L. Thompson on Monday declined to dismiss the proposed =
securities class action, which was filed in 2022 in the US District Court f=
or the Northern District of California. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Thompson rejected Wells Fargo=E2=80=99s argument that its statements weren=
=E2=80=99t misleading because its policy only promised that half of intervi=
ewed candidates would be diverse but didn=E2=80=99t address whether those c=
andidates would be hired.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That argument ign=
ores =E2=80=9Cthe greater context in which the statements were made,=E2=80=
=9D including investor pressure to increase overall diversity at the compan=
y after a series of workplace discrimination scandals at the company, the j=
udge said.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36237924.195389/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc=
3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JzRmk2a0Z5UlZtdy92=
MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB22bfaa5d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the ruling</a>. This is why I=
 like to say that =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud,=E2=80=9D that ev=
ery bad thing that a public company does is also securities fraud. Wells Fa=
rgo did a bad thing. But the badness of the thing is uncertain, amorphous, =
hard to quantify: People were harmed, but not in ways that the legal system=
 can easily reduce to money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the=C2=A0<=
em>financial=C2=A0</em>system can: The bad thing that Wells Fargo did cause=
d its=C2=A0<em>stock=C2=A0</em>to drop, which is a good rough measure of=C2=
=A0<em>how bad it was</em>. The shareholders perform the socially useful se=
rvice of=C2=A0<em>measuring=C2=A0</em>the badness of Wells Fargo=E2=80=99s =
behavior and making it legible to the legal system. And then they =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0no, I=E2=80=99m kidding, mostly their lawyers =E2=80=94=C2=A0get paid=
.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto" cellpaddi=
