om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Not everything is securities fraud (but bad passwords are)</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere in =E2=80=9Cevery bad thing =
that a company does is also securities fraud=E2=80=9D: SolarWinds Corp. is =
a software company that sells network management software that was famously=
 hacked by Russians in 2020. Its stock went down. The US Securities and Exc=
hange Commission sued SolarWinds for pretty straightforward reasons: It sai=
d publicly that it had good information security practices, it actually had=
 bad information security practices, that difference led to a damaging hack=
, and that hack caused the stock to drop. As <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/36237924.195389/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxl=
cy9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMy9jb21wLXByMjAyMy0yMjcucGRm/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cBd9cd3908" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">the SEC said</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A reasonable investor, considering whether to purchase=
 or sell SolarWinds stock, would have considered it important to know the t=
rue state of SolarWinds=E2=80=99 password policies, especially considering =
that these issues were longstanding and potentially affected customer-facin=
g areas such as the Akamai server used to send updates to customers.</p></b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe true state of SolarWind=
s=E2=80=99 password policies=E2=80=9D was that hackers could mess with Sola=
rWinds=E2=80=99 code by guessing the password =E2=80=9Csolarwinds123.=E2=80=
=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/36237924.195389/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMzEvYmFkLXBhc3N3b3Jkcy1hcmUtc2VjdXJpdGllc=
y1mcmF1ZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzMwMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9z=
b3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MzAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9299410e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">we talked about this</a> last y=
ear, when the SEC sued; my headline was =E2=80=9CBad Passwords Are Securiti=
es Fraud.=E2=80=9D But earlier this month SolarWinds succeeded in getting m=
uch of the SEC=E2=80=99s case against it dismissed. As Cleary Gottlieb Stee=
n &amp; Hamilton LLP summarizes the decision in a <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36237924.195389/aHR0cHM6Ly9jbGllbnQuY2xlYXJ=
5Z290dGxpZWIuY29tLzUxLzMzMzIvdXBsb2Fkcy8yMDI0LTA3LTI2LXNkbnktY291cnQtZGlzbW=
lzc2VzLXNldmVyYWwtc2VjLWNsYWltcy1hZ2FpbnN0LXNvbGFyd2luZHMtYW5kLWl0cy1jaXNvL=
nBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa088bc26" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">client memo</a>:</p><blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last week, Judge Paul A. Engelmayer of=
 the Southern District of New York dismissed significant portions of the SE=
C=E2=80=99s case. Judge Engelmayer found that the SEC=E2=80=99s claims base=
d on the Company=E2=80=99s post-incident disclosures, which the agency clai=
med minimized the attack, were ill-pled and amounted to inappropriate secon=
d-guessing. In an issue of first impression, Judge Engelmayer also dismisse=
d the SEC=E2=80=99s internal controls claims, holding that <em>accounting <=
/em>controls could not be reasonably read to encompass <em>cybersecurity </=
em>controls. He also held that the SEC inadequately pled disclosure control=
s failures by the Company.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">=E2=80=9CEvery bad thing that a public company does is securities fraud=
=E2=80=9D is not=C2=A0<em>quite=C2=A0</em>the rule: You also need some <em>=
statement=C2=A0</em>by the company that is made false by the bad thing. Whe=
n Wells Fargo said that it interviewed diverse candidates for its jobs, and=
 it turned out it was fake-interviewing them, that was arguably fraud, but =
it did need to say it. Here, though, the judge ruled that a lot of what Sol=
arWinds said was not really misleading, so could not be fraud, even though =
the company really did do bad things.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>But the case was not entirely dismissed, and bad passwords are still secur=
ities fraud. From <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
36237924.195389/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0h=
CRmRmeElVL3JLZ2xvSE5neXozcy92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB81ffcf27" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
the judge=E2=80=99s ruling</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>The [SEC=E2=80=99s complaint] also adequately alleges that the Security St=
atement [published on SolarWinds=E2=80=99 website before the hack]=C2=A0mat=
erially misrepresented to the public that SolarWinds enforced a strong pass=
word policy. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In essence, th=
e Statement held out SolarWinds as having sophisticated cybersecurity contr=
ols in place and as heeding industry best practices. In reality, based on t=
he pleadings, the company fell way short of even basic requirements of corp=
orate cyber health. Its passwords =E2=80=94 including for key products =E2=
=80=94 were demonstrably weak and the company gave far too many employees u=
nfettered administrative access and privileges, leaving the door wide open =
to hackers and threat actors. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A r=
easonable person contemplating investing in Solar Winds would have viewed t=
he alleged gap between SolarWinds' words and on-the-ground reality as highl=
y consequential-as "significant in making investment decisions." =E2=80=A6 =
Indeed, the business risks presented by such penetrable cybersecurity might=
 well have been material for a company that sold old-fashioned products (e.=
g., furniture or cars). But the specific risks were magnified for SolarWind=
s, whose products (software) had cybersecurity as a key attribute and whose=
 key clients (government agencies and Fortune 500 companies) expected the s=
oftware they purchased to be and remain uncompromised.</p></blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you say you have good passwords and you have ba=
d passwords, that=E2=80=99s securities fraud.</p><table class=3D"header" wi=
